name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510"><gtr:id>46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510</gtr:id><gtr:name>Imperial College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>South Kensington Campus</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Exhibition Road</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>SW7 2AZ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7"><gtr:id>88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of East Anglia</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Earlham Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Norfolk</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>NR4 7TJ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6DC31837-4293-4838-972E-B70F4401FDE0"><gtr:id>6DC31837-4293-4838-972E-B70F4401FDE0</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Heiner</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Grosskurth</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1A3B6D92-2B45-4568-B799-E1468EDF6002"><gtr:id>1A3B6D92-2B45-4568-B799-E1468EDF6002</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Brent</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Wolff</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U950080936"><gtr:id>9AB204B9-E991-473E-B62B-1098E38513F6</gtr:id><gtr:title>Social Science Programme / HIV Status Disclosure and Sexual Behaviour Study Project</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U950080936</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>A pregnant woman who has been diagnosed as HIV-positive when she attended antenatal clinic based voluntary counselling and testing services is confronted with an emotionally very difficult situation. Apart from the challenge to have to come to terms with the news about her infection, she faces the dilemma to either disclose the news to her partner and possibly risk stigmatisation and marital conflict or to ignore feeding advice and other suggestions offered that may reduce the risk of mother-to-child transmission. Research is conducted to better understand the difficulties mothers are exposed to. It is hoped that the results will lead to information that can help designing interventions such as assisted disclosure, to support mothers in achieving better adherence to PMTCT advice.|Similarly, disclosure of HIV status to the partner or to another significant person may help patients on ART to better adhere to treatment guidelines. Disclosure seems however not always to be easy even for patients who know their status for a long time. Research aiming to better understand the determinants of disclosure behaviour will be helpful to achieve better treatment results. Another interesting behavioural research question is to what extent successful ART will modify sexual behaviour, and this research is likely to help designing messages and bring about behavioural changes that may protect the HIV infected patient and his or her sexual partners from additional risks.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Purpose: To assess the effect that the participation in prevention of mother-to-child transmission (PMTCT) services and antiretroviral treatment (ART) services have on sexual behaviour and on HIV status disclosure behaviour; and to explore how disclosure to significant others (defined as a spouse, sexual partner, relative or friend) influences compliance with treatment requirements. The results of this work are expected to help designing better prevention and care strategies for people living with HIV infection or AIDS.|Methods: Study of the effect of PMTCT services: mothers are recruited consecutively from the PMTCT services at Entebbe Hospital, to be interviewed before delivery at the time of receiving preventive therapy, post-delivery at their babies 6-week and 9-month immunization visits, and after 18-months. In-depth interviews (IDIs) are conducted at the same time points. Study of the effect of ART services: This involves the consecutive recruitment and follow-up of women and men receiving ART through the DART trial (see separate abstract) and of HIV-positive clients from the Entebbe Clinical Cohort who have not yet started ART. Face-to-face questionnaire interviews are conducted every 8 months; IDIs are conducted among a subset of respondents.|In addition, an anonymous self-administered questionnaire (SAQ) is repeatedly applied to patients who receive ART and attend the study clinic for routine follow-up visits. This component allows testing of a low-cost model for monitoring trends in risk behaviour in HIV related trials. The use of a SAQ was hypothesised to enhance the validity of the information provided by participants. The questionnaire has been designed for a low literacy setting using simple yes/no answers represented by icons that can be ticked or circled. SAQs are explained to participants, and private booths are provided to fill them. Trained interviewers are available to give assistance if required. Care is taken that they cannot see the responses given.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-04-01</gtr:start